Preheat your oven to 170°C. Bring a large #saucepan{} of @water{750%ml} to the boil and stir in the @vegetable stock powder{1}. Remove the pan of stock from the heat - we will use it later. Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1} into small pieces. Trim, peel and grate the @beetroot{2}(peeled and grated on the coarse side of a grater). TIP: Wear gloves to avoid staining your hands! Pick the @thyme{¼%bunch} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks).

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{2%tbsp} in another large saucepan over medium heat. TIP: Add a good knob of butter if you have some! Stir the onion, beetroot and thyme into the pan and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook until the onion and beetroot are soft, stirring occasionally, ~{10%minutes}. Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(grated or pressed). Chop the @dill{1%bunch}(chopped, stalks and all). Return the stock to low heat and make the salad dressing.

Put the @walnuts{20%g} on a #baking tray{} and pop onto the middle shelf of your oven to toast, until lightly coloured, ~{8-9%minutes}. Meanwhile, zest the @lemon{1} and cut in half. In a large #bowl{} combine the lemon zest, half of the lemon juice, the olive oil, @cider & horseradish wholegrain mustard{¼%tsp}, a pinch of @?sugar{} (optional) and salt and pepper to taste. When ready, remove the walnuts from the oven, roughly chop and add to the bowl.

> If you have some white wine in your kitchen, you can add a splash now. Let the alcohol bubble off for a few minutes to mellow the flavour. If you don't have any wine don't worry, just move right on to step 5. The risotto will still taste delicious!

When the onion and beetroot are soft, add the garlic, stir and cook for ~{1%minute}. Increase the heat slightly, then add the @orzo{180%g} to pan. Stir until evenly coated.

Add a ladleful of the stock to the orzo and stir it in gently. Once the liquid is almost fully absorbed, add another ladleful, continue stirring. Keep adding the stock, stirring all the time, until the orzo is 'al dente' - cooked but with a tiny bit of firmness left in the middle, ~{10-15%minutes}. TIP: If you've added all the stock but the orzo isn't quite ready, just add a splash of water and continue cooking.

Once the orzotto is cooked, finish by mixing in the @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g} and a squeeze of lemon juice. Season with salt and pepper to taste.

Add the @wild rocket{40%g} to the bowl with the walnut dressing in. Toss together to coat the leaves. Divide the risotto between plates and top with a good dollop of @soured cream{150%g} and the chopped dill. Top with the rocket salad. Wow!